### TITLE ###
NullInUnionTypedAssignmentSuggestsTQuestion
### DESCRIPTION ###
Baseline: typed-assignment `x: int|null = ...` already produced
the helpful "Rad spells nullable types as T?" suggestion.
Regression lock for that path.
### INPUT ###
a: int|null = null
### STDOUT ###
# Identifier types
  a @ 1:1 -> <no-type>

# Symbol types
  a (local): int

# Diagnostics
  [error] RAD10009 @ 1:7 - 'null' is not a valid type in a union
    help: Rad spells nullable types as 'T?' (e.g. 'int?', not 'int|null')
  [error] RAD30001 @ 1:15 - Value of type 'null' is not assignable to declared type 'int'
    help: To allow null here, declare the slot as 'int?'
### TITLE ###
NullInUnionFnNamedParamSuggestsTQuestion
### DESCRIPTION ###
A named-fn parameter `fn f(x: int|null):` now fires the same
suggestion - previously this produced a generic "Invalid
function syntax" / RAD10001 because the parser bailed before
wrapping the union in a fn_param_or_return_type.
### INPUT ###
fn f(x: int|null):
    print(x)
### STDOUT ###
# Identifier types
  print @ 2:5 -> dynamic
  x @ 2:11 -> int

# Symbol types
  f (fn): fn(int) -> void
  x (param): int

# Diagnostics
  [error] RAD10009 @ 1:12 - 'null' is not a valid type in a union
    help: Rad spells nullable types as 'T?' (e.g. 'int?', not 'int|null')
### TITLE ###
NullInUnionLambdaParamSuggestsTQuestion
### DESCRIPTION ###
Same enforcement for inline lambdas. The ERROR attaches to
the fn_lambda node when the param annotation has the bad
`int|null` shape.
### INPUT ###
f = fn(x: int|null): x
### STDOUT ###
# Identifier types
  f @ 1:1 -> <no-type>
  x @ 1:22 -> int

# Symbol types
  f (local): fn(int) -> int
  x (param): int

# Diagnostics
  [error] RAD10009 @ 1:14 - 'null' is not a valid type in a union
    help: Rad spells nullable types as 'T?' (e.g. 'int?', not 'int|null')
### TITLE ###
NullInUnionFnTypeSuggestsTQuestion
### DESCRIPTION ###
A fn-type annotation like `fn(int|null) -> int` previously
produced a bare "Unexpected '|null'" without the helpful
T? suggestion. Now the suggestion is attached.
### INPUT ###
fn process(cb: fn(int|null) -> int):
    print(cb(1))
### STDOUT ###
# Identifier types
  print @ 2:5 -> dynamic
  cb @ 2:11 -> fn(int) -> int

# Symbol types
  cb (param): fn(int) -> int
  process (fn): fn(fn(int) -> int) -> void

# Diagnostics
  [error] RAD10009 @ 1:22 - 'null' is not a valid type in a union
    help: Rad spells nullable types as 'T?' (e.g. 'int?', not 'int|null')
### TITLE ###
NullInUnionFnReturnTypeSuggestsTQuestion
### DESCRIPTION ###
The return-type position is the messiest case - the parser
collapses the whole header into an outer ERROR with the bad
union nested as an inner ERROR. The inner one fires the
suggestion; the outer one stays at the generic message so
the user gets exactly one help hint.
### INPUT ###
fn f() -> int|null:
    return null
### STDOUT ###
# Identifier types
  (none)

# Symbol types
  (none)

# Diagnostics
  [error] RAD10001 @ 1:1 - Invalid syntax
  [error] RAD10009 @ 1:14 - 'null' is not a valid type in a union
    help: Rad spells nullable types as 'T?' (e.g. 'int?', not 'int|null')
### TITLE ###
BareNullTypedAssignmentSuggestsTQuestion
### DESCRIPTION ###
`a: null = ...` - the bare-null type annotation. Sibling of
the in-union case above. Previously fired a generic
"Unexpected ': null'" with no hint toward T?; now points
users at the canonical nullable spelling.
### INPUT ###
a: null = 5
### STDOUT ###
# Identifier types
  a @ 1:1 -> <no-type>

# Symbol types
  a (local): int

# Diagnostics
  [error] RAD10009 @ 1:2 - 'null' is not a declarable type
    help: Declare the slot as 'T?' (e.g. 'int?') if the value may be null
### TITLE ###
BareNullInsideFunctionSuggestsTQuestion
### DESCRIPTION ###
The exact repro from kan card null-type-annotation:
`c: null = x` inside an else-branch where `x` is narrowed
to null. The typed-assign with bare-null gets the helpful
suggestion instead of the bare "Unexpected ': null'".
### INPUT ###
fn f(x: int?):
    if x != null:
        a = x
    else:
        c: null = x
### STDOUT ###
# Identifier types
  x @ 2:8 -> int?
  a @ 3:9 -> <no-type>
  x @ 3:13 -> int
  c @ 5:9 -> <no-type>
  x @ 5:19 -> null

# Symbol types
  a (local): int
  c (local): null
  f (fn): fn(int?) -> void
  x (param): int?

# Diagnostics
  [error] RAD10009 @ 5:10 - 'null' is not a declarable type
    help: Declare the slot as 'T?' (e.g. 'int?') if the value may be null
### TITLE ###
NullValueAssignmentDoesNotTrigger
### DESCRIPTION ###
Regression lock: `x = null` (value-position null, no type
annotation) is fine and must not trigger the bare-null
suggestion. The check is gated on type-annotation parents.
### INPUT ###
x = null
### STDOUT ###
# Identifier types
  x @ 1:1 -> <no-type>

# Symbol types
  x (local): null

# Diagnostics
  (none)
